- The United States' pivot to Asia and its overall repositioning of its global interests has also had an impact on Russia. The U.S. has been moving out of the Middle East and into Asia. U.S. defense attaché in Ukraine writes about this shift in U.S. policy. Russia sees itself being moved out of Eastern Europe as a result and views increased U.S. military presence in the Asia Pacific, on its borders as a threat. In the opinion of many Russians, the media in the U.S. and E.U. are falling for the sonorous promises of a benevolent America towards the rest of the world. This is why under Putin, Russia is on the watch-tower and is expected to play the leading role in the region.

All the crisis in the Middle East, involvement of America to an extent without much achievement and a growing role of Russia because of the seizure of Crimea and its need to come up with a constructive way out of the situation in Syria and Presidential elections looming in Ukraine in May 2014 are all part of a serious juggling game. The U.S. will have to accept the new reality and make its policies, Russia will have to project pragmatism in its stand and places of influence and the E.U. too will have to retrench and reposition itself or discover
